		<tr>
		  <td width="135" class="forum_boardrow2" style="border-width: 0px 0px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="messageuser31125707" style="padding-bottom: 2px;"><a href="/profile/Parial"><strong>Parial</strong></a></div>
		  
		  <a href="/profile/Parial"><img src="http://cdn.myanimelist.net/images/useravatars/235149.png" vspace="2" border="0"></a>
		  <br>
		  Offline<br>
		  Joined: Sep 2009<br>
		  Posts: 269
		  </td>
		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message31125707"><div class="spoiler"><input type="button" class="button" onClick="this.nextSibling.nextSibling.style.display='block';this.style.display='none';" value="Show spoiler"> <span class="spoiler_content" style="display:none"><input type="button" class="button" onClick="this.parentNode.style.display='none';this.parentNode.parentNode.childNodes[0].style.display='block';" value="Hide spoiler"><br>Luckily enough I already discussed the Aria franchise with a certain Ran fan long ago, so I'm mostly going to repost my thoughts with a few (read: a bunch of) changes here and there.<!--spoiler--></span></div> <br />
<br />
Aria, while certainly not the first anime series centered around the daily lives of a group of girls, is one of the very few to blend characters into the schematization of a grand setting. Neo-Venezia is a magical place, and what a better way to explore its wonders than through the guidance of its water spirits, the undines? Due to this, the spellbinding appeal of the city can be seen extended to the very candor that permeates the daily lives of the cast. It is a simplistic beauty ingrained in every facet of the show, being a key factor in what makes Aria such a delightful ride from beginning to end. <br />
<br />
Undoubtedly, Aria's atmosphere can be said to be one of the key pillars of the franchise. If we were to closely analyze what makes it so distinguished, there would be a multitude of interconnected factors at play: the gradual exploration of Neo-Venezia, the meticulous cast-setting integration, the heavenly soundtrack–so flawlessly integrated–and even the characters' growth as undines. Picking one most important element is a difficult task, but they all, to varying extents, provide and enhance immersion. Though naturally, this will differ from viewer to viewer. Personally, I credit the divinely soothing atmosphere to the execution of the setting as a whole– its richness providing a magnificent backdrop for the unfolding of the undines' lives. It is a truly gratifying experience to watch them so wholeheartedly embrace Aqua, its history and its culture, growing along with it. As the popular saying goes, <em>"Smile at the world, and the world will surely smile back at you."</em><br />
<br />
The first installment in the anime franchise is Aria the Animation. Although working well as an introduction to Aria's world, it seems to be a consensus that among all three seasons it is the weakest one. The laidback dialogue, the atmospheric soundtrack and the season's slow but captivating episode progression are arguably its strongest assets, but on the other hand, not much is established in terms of characterization and setting. <br />
<br />
For such reason, Aria The Natural can be seen as the real point where the anime series starts shining bright, as Neo-Venezia itself becomes the main star of the show. The undines work superbly in serving as a link between the viewer and the city, in a way that their immense fondness for their profession and their home make them a meaningful part of the setting, rather than simply thrown into it–as we start loving the characters, we start loving Neo-Venezia, and vice-versa. The existence of supernatural elements in the story, in particular, builds a wonderful sense of mystique around the setting. Contrived as such elements might sound at first, they fit the tone and context of the show perfectly. Tone, because their integration is gradual, unobtrusive and tightly tied to Akari's fanciful, almost child-like world-view – out of all characters, she is the only one exposed to the supernatural. Context, due to Venice's cultural background providing a unique backdrop for the integration of fantasy. The headless lady and Caith Sith and his cat followers are the two main examples that come to mind. The former I'm pretty sure was influenced by Venice's folklore, though I can't seem to find a source on it. The latter has a very interesting historical connection<strong><!--link--><a href="http://www.fictionalcities.co.uk/veniceandcats.htm" rel="nofollow">[1]</a><!--link--><a href="http://europeforvisitors.com/venice/articles/cats_of_venice.htm" rel="nofollow">[2]</a></strong> to the role cats used to play in controlling the mice population and in helping reduce the transmission of diseases in Venice's old days. This would explain why the cats are portrayed in a role akin to that of guardians in Aria. All in all, Aria deftly borrows cultural elements from Venice in order to create something of its own, and this can be seen reflected in Neo-Venezia's customs and legends. By having Akari interact with the city's very folklore, the show gracefully shines light onto the beautiful cultural mosaic that is Aria's setting.<br />
<br />
The Origination, as a culmination of everything that has gone before, builds upon the previous seasons' foundations splendidly. Given the gradual build-up throughout the seasons, The Origination coalesces with The Animation and The Natural both thematically and narratively, as the characters transition into new life stages and move along with the winds of change, even if very reluctantly at first. It is Aria's own nuanced way of transmitting the idea that life is a continuous process of change and that nothing is eternal, providing the audience with a very heartfelt goodbye to Neo-Venezia and its undines. In my view, the reason Aria so efficiently manages to create a connection with the viewer, is due to its uncomplicated yet powerful storytelling–once again, I'd like to emphasize Aria's simplistic beauty. Out of all three seasons, The Origination is by far my favorite, for embodying the harmonious and soothing spirit of the franchise and ending with such a meaningful message. As a slice of life with a clear sense of purpose, The Origination is truly a stand-out in the anime medium.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
